We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the concerned officials and employees to submit the feasibility study (FS) and business plan (BP) for the Municipal Inland Resort and Training Center to establish the economic and social gains to be derived there from as a local economic enterprise and as a performance measure in evaluating its sustainability. Otherwise, submit an explanation as to why no FS and BP was conducted prior to establishment of the structures.
The aforementioned audit observation was communicated to management through Audit Observation Memorandum No. 2022-07 dated April 8, 2022.
Management Comment
Initially, the Management planned to construct an Olympic size swimming pool in Cabatuan National Comprehensive High School in order to boost its sports program but due to the implementation of K-12 program, the space allotted for the swimming pool was utilized for the construction of a school building. Consequently, they decided to construct the swimming pool and training center in Brgy. Salacay, Cabatuan.
The Management justified that the construction of the swimming pool and training center was supported with a feasibility study on the proposed design of swimming pool complex. The idea to make the facility as an economic enterprise was made after the structures were established. They further added that the feasibility study for the operation of the Municipal Inland Resort and Training Center is not necessary because some of the structures were already existing.
Moreover, they agreed that there is a need for Business Plan and for this purpose, the CEEDO Board is working closely with the Sangguniang Bayan in order to formulate the revenue ordinance in relation to the operation of the said facility.
Auditor’s Rejoinder
While we acknowledge that it was the LGU’s intention to make the Municipal Inland Resort and Training Center as an economic enterprise, this was not supported with a feasibility study as required under DBM Local Budget Circular No. 111 and Manual on the Setting Up and Operation of Local Economic Enterprises (LEEs). The Audit Team would like to emphasize that economic enterprises may be established after the conduct of a feasibility study (FS) which shall show proof of its economic/social viability in the long term in terms of sufficient demand and that the prospective constituency users are able and are willing to pay for the use of the LEE output.
Moreover, the submitted cover and approval page of the feasibility study for the proposed design of swimming pool complex is not sufficient to support the establishment of the facility as an economic enterprise as it only pertains to the structural design of the facility. The content of the study was not submitted; thus, the Audit Team is unable to assess whether it establishes the viability and marketability of the said resort and training center.
Furthermore, the Management’s decision to make the facility as an economic enterprise was done only after the structures were established. However, the Manual on the Setting Up and Operation of LEE provides the steps on how to plan and set-up a new LEE as follows:
Evaluate Whether the LGU Should Engage in LEE;
Conduct a Feasibility Study for the Proposed LEE;
Assess Potential LEE Financing Sources;
Select Financing Source;
Present the Feasibility Study Findings and Recommended Financing Source to the LCE’;
If the LCE decides to create the LEE: Prepare a 5-Year Business Plan;
Prepare and Present the Proposal for the Establishment of the LEE (Feasibility Study and Business Plan) to the Local Sanggunian as Basis for the Enactment of an Ordinance Creating the LEE; and
Enact the Ordinance Creating the LEE
Based on the foregoing, the LGU should have undergone the abovementioned steps in deciding whether to engage in a particular LEE as the LEE shall be self-liquidating and must not represent a drain on the LGUs resources. Hence, this office recommends the submission of the abovementioned requirements.

We recommended that Management:
provide a written explanation on the non-deduction of 1% retention as   warranty of these procured goods and strictly comply with the provisions of RA 9184 to deduct 1% retention from the payments of goods to the suppliers, and ensure that conditions set forth by the law are observed;
submit full accounting of these goods, duly received by the recipients including their complete addresses duly noted and supervised by the MSWDO;
submit list of patients/beneficiaries of the test kits with their complete addresses including other related information as basis in undergoing test, duly noted by the Municipal Health Officer; and
ensure completeness of documentation before effecting payment on all transactions, to comply with the requirements of pertinent rules and regulations.

We recommended management to:

[a] Constitute a technical committee to assess the existing stall occupants if they are compliant with the terms and conditions embodied in the contract prior to issuing lease contract agreement and ensure that all these occupants are covered with the same. 

[b] Conduct measurement of each of the stalls in the new and old public, market;

[c] Update the inventory of market stalls and provide all the necessary information to facilitate computation of exact rental to be collected;

[d] For the stall occupants with delinquent rentals, business license should not be renewed unless back rentals are first settled.

We recommended that management:

[1] Ensure that the services of the Municipal Cooperative Officer, being a government official, focused mainly on the duties and functions embodied under the Local Government Code; 

[2] Require Mr. Macugay to divest himself as manager in the said cooperative within the period stated in the said Act in order to escape occurrence of issue on the conflict-of-interest;

[3] Cause the transfer of the Office of the CASADECO outside of the Office of the MCO; and 

[4] Require the Municipal Cooperative Officer to submit justification why he assumed the position as Manager of the said cooperative knowing the provision of R.A. 6713.

